<TI>Case Law: Section 1</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 1</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1933707">
<SOC>2200334 Ontario Inc. v. Landmark Vehicle Leasing Corp.</SOC>
<CITE>2019 ONSC 7532</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 21114</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>11 P.P.S.A.C. (4th) 273</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>At issue was whether the plaintiff, Toronto Motorsports Park (TMP), was
required to comply with ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 56, ^SO2002c30SchA 57, ^SO2002c30SchA
58(1) and ^SO2002c30SchA 59 (Motor Vehicle Repairs) of the Act and failure to do
so would trigger the provision of the <EM>Repair and Storage Liens Act</EM>
that declares that no repairer's lien arises if these provisions of the CPA are
not complied with. The vehicle was leased to a corporation for use by that
corporation's president. The individual arranged for the repair work on the
vehicle, a Ferrari. The Court held that when TMP undertook to repair the
Ferrari, the person requesting the repairs was doing so as president of a
corporation, not in a personal capacity. Therefore, the CPA did not apply to
this transaction.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1155619">
<SOC>Graham v. Imperial Parking Canada Corp.</SOC>
<CITE>2010 ONSC 4982</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2010 CarswellOnt 6941</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>74 B.L.R. (4th) 172</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2010] O.J. No. 3898</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>leave to appeal refused</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1185798">
<CITE>2011 ONSC 991</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2011 CarswellOnt 3282</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>85 B.L.R. (4th) 167</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>279 O.A.C. 342</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2011] O.J. No. 2027</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that not all &ldquo;consumer agreements&rdquo; are &ldquo;future
performance agreements&rdquo; and an agreement for parking services was held to
be outside the ambit of the CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1359557">
<SOC>Collett v. Reliance Home Comfort Limited Partnership</SOC>
<CITE>2012 ONCA 821</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 14920</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>299 O.A.C. 119</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 5555</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>leave to appeal refused</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1383741">
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 4858</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 4859</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<SOC>Szilvasy v. Reliance Home Comfort Limited Partnership</SOC>
<CITE>455 N.R. 396 (note)</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>320 O.A.C. 398 (note)</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that the rental of a water heater did constitute a consumer
agreement under the CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1187383">
<SOC>Weller v. Reliance Home Comfort Ltd. Partnership</SOC>
<CITE>2011 ONSC 3148</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2011 CarswellOnt 3835</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>335 D.L.R. (4th) 690</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2011] O.J. No. 2344</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1195382">
<CITE>2011 ONSC 4103</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2011 CarswellOnt 6947</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>affirmed</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1282618">
<CITE>2012 ONCA 360</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 6714</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>110 O.R. (3d) 743</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>350 D.L.R. (4th) 301</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>291 O.A.C. 388</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
