</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that purchase and sale of the defendants' products were not
&ldquo;consumer transactions&rdquo; under the CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF>
<SOC>Body Science Ltd. v. 1697027 Ontario Ltd. (c.o.b. Premier Auto Service)</SOC>
<CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 2928</CITE>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that claims under the CPA would not apply in respect of a
vehicle registered in the name of a corporate entity.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1241399">
<SOC>Ontario (Ministry of Consumer Services) v. K-Tech Building Systems Inc.</SOC>
<CITE>2012 ONCJ 219</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 4865</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>13 C.L.R. (4th) 187</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 1764</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This case was decided by a justice of the peace. The
Court held that a construction of a proposed cottage would be &ldquo;goods&rdquo;
for the purposes of the CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1358550">
<SOC>Ramdath v. George Brown College of Applied Arts and Technology</SOC>
<CITE>2012 ONSC 6173</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 14486</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>113 O.R. (3d) 531</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 5389</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>affirmed</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1397517">
<CITE>2013 ONCA 468</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 9183</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<SOC>Ramdath v. Brown (George) College of Applied Arts and Technology</SOC>
<CITE>307 O.A.C. 196</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 3151</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This is a class proceeding. The Court held that college
students are included in the definition of &ldquo;consumers&rdquo; in s.
^SO2002c30SchA 1 of the Act. Even though college students may be taking business
or professional programs to obtain job credentials for the future, they are
still &ldquo;consumers&rdquo; of educational services. Only if someone already
has an established (i.e. current) business and purchases educational services to
further that business do they fall outside the protection of the CPA. A court
will generally find someone to have a business purpose if they are acting in a
professional or business capacity at the time of the transaction.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1689334">
<SOC>407 ETR Concession Co. v. Day</SOC>
<CITE>2016 ONCA 709</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2016 CarswellOnt 14831</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>133 O.R. (3d) 762</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>403 D.L.R. (4th) 385</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>1 M.V.R. (7th) 175</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2016] O.J. No. 5006</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>leave to appeal refused</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1732642">
<SOC>Day v. 407 ETR Concession Co.</SOC>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 6258</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 6259</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2016] S.C.C.A. No. 509</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that the transponder lease agreement in question was not a
business agreement because in the application for a transponder, the applicant
checked the box for &ldquo;personal use&rdquo;, not business use. The Court
further noted that the applicant qualified as a consumer as defined in s.
^SO2002c30SchA 1 of this Act.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1789322">
<SOC>Schnarr v. Blue Mountain Resorts Limited</SOC>
<CITE>2018 ONCA 313</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2018 CarswellOnt 4786</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>140 O.R. (3d) 241</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>47 C.C.L.T. (4th) 187</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>424 D.L.R. (4th) 77</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1794059">
<CITE>2018 ONCA 400</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2018 CarswellOnt 6266</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>47 C.C.L.T. (4th) 215</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>leave to appeal refused</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1847959">
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 1729</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 1730</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2018] S.C.C.A. No. 187</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1810703">
<CITE>2018 ONCA 668</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2018 CarswellOnt 12034</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>47 C.C.L.T. (4th) 218</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>24 C.P.C. (8th) 290</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 7 and ^SO2002c30SchA 9 of the CPA
fundamentally undermined the purpose of s. 3(3) of <EM>Occupiers' Liability Act</EM>,
and were irreconcilable and conflicted. As such, the more specific provisions of
the <EM>Occupiers' Liability Act</EM> prevailed over the general provisions in
CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1791288">
<SOC>Cornerstone Select Properties Inc. v. Matthews and Matthews</SOC>
<CITE>2018 ONSC 679</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2018 CarswellOnt 5456</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>82 C.L.R. (4th) 92</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that a renovation contract for investment property qualified
as a &ldquo;consumer contract&rdquo;.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1859365">
<SOC>TELUS Communications Inc. v. Wellman</SOC>
<CITE>2019 CSC 19</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 SCC 19</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 4913</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 4914</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2019] 2 S.C.R. 144</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>93 B.L.R. (5th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>32 C.P.C. (8th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>433 D.L.R. (4th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This is a class proceeding. The plaintiffs disputed the
arbitration clause in the phone service contracts between the class members and
TELUS Communications Inc. The Court held that the arbitration clause is invalid
to the extent that it violates the rights of class members who qualify as
&ldquo;consumers&rdquo; under the CPA. In particular, the Court refused to
enforce the arbitration clause against consumers because it infringed ss.
^SO2002c30SchA 7(2) and ^SO2002c30SchA 8 of the CPA by preventing consumers from
commencing or joining a class action. Section ^SO2002c30SchA 7(5) of the CPA
also restricted the Court from ordering a stay of proceedings under the <EM>Arbitration
Act</EM> against consumers. However, the Court held that business customers did
not qualify as &ldquo;consumers&rdquo; under the CPA and therefore, they could
not invoke protections that were available to consumers under ss. ^SO2002c30SchA
7(2), ^SO2002c30SchA 7(5), and ^SO2002c30SchA 8.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1908664">
<SOC>Cullaton v. MDG Newmarket Inc.</SOC>
<CITE>2019 ONSC 6432</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 18349</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>A motion for certification of a class action alleging that an HVAC rental
company breached the CPA. The alleged facts are that once the HVAC equipment was
rented a security interest was put in place against the consumer's property.
This lien was not authorized by the rental agreement (which was &ldquo;misleading
and deceptive&rdquo;) and the &ldquo;buyout program&rdquo; for the equipment
also went undisclosed. Common issues posed by the potential class include breach
of ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 14 and ^SO2002c30SchA 15 of the CPA (unfair practice) as
well as the regulations under the Act regarding leasing as well as the direct
agreement requirements in Part IV. The Court also engages in a summary judgment
analysis on whether the rental agreements were in contravention of the CPA's
requirements and regulations. The Court held that there was a genuine issue for
trial, mainly that Home Trust Company was not necessarily a &ldquo;supplier&rdquo;
under the CPA and the plaintiffs were raising new points of law that could not
be settled without a trial. Partial summary judgment was denied.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="2006470">
<SOC>1179640 Ontario Limited v. DaSilva</SOC>
<CITE>2020 ONSC 5456</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2020 CarswellOnt 12976</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>64 M.V.R. (7th) 219</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>A Divisional Court appeal from a Small Claims Court decision held that
consumer approval to motor vehicle repairs cannot rely on yet undetermined
details (not yet provided to the consumer), and that an insurer does not have
the authority to authorize repairs on behalf of the consumer.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:2(1)" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>2(1)</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 2(1)</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 2(1)</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1635985">
<SOC>Jhajj v. Ha</SOC>
<CITE>2015 ONSC 7326</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2015 CarswellOnt 17849</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>56 C.L.R. (4th) 143</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>Although it is preferable for the trial judge to bring the Act to the
attention of the parties and permit argument on issues relating to the Act prior
to ruling on them, where this is not done, there is no prejudice by the
application of the Act and by the conclusion that it imposes an implied warranty
with respect to services supplied to the consumer notwithstanding the absence of
an express warranty in the contract.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:2(2)" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>2(2)</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 2(2)</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 2(2)</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1241399">
<SOC>Ontario (Ministry of Consumer Services) v. K-Tech Building Systems Inc.</SOC>
<CITE>2012 ONCJ 219</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 4865</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>13 C.L.R. (4th) 187</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 1764</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This case was decided by a justice of the peace. The
Court held that a construction of a proposed cottage would not be a transaction
involving &ldquo;real property&rdquo; and thus not exempted under s.
^SO2002c30SchA 2(2)(f) of the CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1716067">
<SOC>Bernstein v. Peoples Trust Co.</SOC>
<CITE>2017 ONSC 752</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 1361</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>97 C.P.C. (7th) 286</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1729471">
<CITE>2017 ONSC 2189</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5120</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that it was not plain and obvious that prepaid payment cards
were not subject to the Act.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1785185">
<SOC>Rush v. De Ruiter</SOC>
<CITE>2018 ONSC 1210</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2018 CarswellOnt 3357</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that nursing services are prescribed professional services
that are regulated under a statute of Ontario and thus fall outside the scope of
the consumer protection scheme.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1868224">
<SOC>Bernstein v. Peoples Trust Company</SOC>
<CITE>2019 ONSC 2867</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 7328</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1884293">
<CITE>2019 ONSC 4675</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 12825</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1901101">
<CITE>2019 ONSC 6076</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 17202</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This is a class proceeding. The Court held that Peoples
Trust Company's Single Load Prepaid Cards (&ldquo;SLP cards&rdquo;) are not a
financial product exempt under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 2(2)(c) from the operation of
the CPA because they were marketed as gifts, which by their nature are generally
intended for personal purposes. Instead, the Court found that the SLP cards are
open loop gift cards regulated by O. Reg. 17/05 and indistinguishable from mall
cards. In contrast, the Court held that Peoples Trust Company's General Purpose
Reloadable Prepaid Cards (&ldquo;GPR cards&rdquo;) are a financial product
exempt from the CPA by virtue of s. ^SO2002c30SchA 2(2)(c) because, through the
means of access to a payment network, the end of GPR cards is banking.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1876689">
<SOC>Evans v. Mattamy Homes Limited</SOC>
<CITE>2019 ONSC 3883</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 10081</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>95 B.L.R. (5th) 333</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The plaintiffs brought an action for rescission of agreements for the
purchase and sale of pre-construction homes along with damages. The defendants
brought a motion for an order staying the action in accordance with the
arbitration clause in the agreements. The Court acknowledged that the CPA was
enacted to prevent arbitration clauses from binding consumers in certain types
of consumer contracts. However, the Ontario legislature specifically endorsed
arbitration as an appropriate dispute resolution forum in the context of real
estate transactions by excluding real estate transactions in s. ^SO2002c30SchA
2(2)(f) of the CPA.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
