</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The plaintiff purchased a season pass at a ski resort and signed a waiver
for recreational use of the property. While skiing at the defendant's ski
resort, the plaintiff got injured and thus filed a motion claiming that s.
^SO2002c30SchA 7(1) of the CPA be applied to vitiate the defendant's waiver of
liability. The Court held that by operation of s. ^SO2002c30SchA 7(1) of the
CPA, the defendant cannot disclaim liability for any breach of the warranty
contemplated by s. ^SO2002c30SchA 9(1) of the CPA. As such, the lower Court read
down the waiver to exclude claims that involved the protection of substantive
and procedural rights contemplated by the CPA, while the remainder of the waiver
was held to be enforceable. On appeal, the ONCA held that ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 7
and ^SO2002c30SchA 9 of CPA fundamentally undermined the purpose of s. 3(3) of
the <EM>Occupiers' Liability Act</EM> (&ldquo;OLA&rdquo;). These sections under
the CPA were irreconcilable and conflicted. Accordingly, the more specific
provisions of the OLA prevailed over the general provisions in CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1859365">
<SOC>TELUS Communications Inc. v. Wellman</SOC>
<CITE>2019 CSC 19</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 SCC 19</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 4913</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 4914</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2019] 2 S.C.R. 144</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>93 B.L.R. (5th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>32 C.P.C. (8th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>433 D.L.R. (4th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This is a class proceeding. The plaintiffs disputed the
arbitration clause in the phone service contracts between the class members and
TELUS Communications Inc. The Court held that the arbitration clause is invalid
to the extent that it violates the rights of class members who qualify as
&ldquo;consumers&rdquo; under the CPA. In particular, the Court refused to
enforce the arbitration clause against consumers because it infringed ss.
^SO2002c30SchA 7(2) and ^SO2002c30SchA 8 of the CPA by preventing consumers from
commencing or joining a class action. Section ^SO2002c30SchA 7(5) of the CPA
also restricted the Court from ordering a stay of proceedings under the <EM>Arbitration
Act</EM> against consumers. However, the Court held that business customers did
not qualify as &ldquo;consumers&rdquo; under the CPA and therefore, they could
not invoke protections that were available to consumers under ss. ^SO2002c30SchA
7(2), ^SO2002c30SchA 7(5), and ^SO2002c30SchA 8.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="2021180">
<SOC>Gupta v. Lindal Cedar Homes Ltd.</SOC>
<CITE>2020 ONSC 7524</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2020 CarswellOnt 17743</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>A current homeowner attempted to rely on the prior owner's contract with a
supplier of homebuilding materials, in a motion to reopen a decision rendered
without any submissions regarding the CPA. The case has significant limitations
on its value as jurisprudence. Court held that arbitration clauses not
prohibited by s. ^SO2002c30SchA 7 of CPA; only disputes arising under the CPA
are subject to such clauses.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
