<CITE>330 O.A.C. 44</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that an estimate that was never acted upon for the purpose
for which it was given cannot fall within the Act. Specifically, the Court held
that an estimate that is given for partial performance of a contract is not
captured by s. ^SO2002c30SchA 10 of the Act.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:11" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>11</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 11</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 11</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1668245">
<SOC>Tecton Construction Inc. v. Yeung</SOC>
<CITE>2016 ONSC 3039</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2016 CarswellOnt 8090</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>68 C.L.R. (4th) 327</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>A clause in a contract that required changes to be in writing did not
preclude a home renovator's claims for compensation for work agreed to orally.
This clause was found to apply to all renovation work completed, whether within
the scope of the written contract or not, based on the provision (s. 11) that
any ambiguity should be resolved in favour of the defendant homeowners. However,
the Court ordered that the consumer is bound by the agreement because it would
be inequitable for the consumer not to be bound, as per s. 93(2). It would have
been inequitable for the defendant homeowners to receive the benefit of the
invoiced items without paying for them.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1286448">
<SOC>Jonker's Lawn Care Inc. v. DBG Canada Ltd.</SOC>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 7954</CITE>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court found that there was no ambiguity in respect of a service contract
as the defendant did not fall within the meaning of &ldquo;consumer&rdquo; for
the CPA to apply.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:13" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>13</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 13</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 13</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1284984">
<SOC>Wright v. United Parcel Service Canada Ltd.</SOC>
<CITE>2012 ONSC 3287</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 7523</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>295 O.A.C. 385</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 2705</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>According to the Court, in a class action certification, whether brokerage
services constituted &ldquo;unsolicited services&rdquo; would depend on the
specific facts of the consignee's knowledge of the defendant's intention to
perform brokerage services for which it would charge brokerage fees, and the
extent to which the consignee agreed to pay, or acquiesced in, the payment of
such fees in the face of such knowledge.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1499718">
<SOC>Action Auto Leasing &amp; Gallery Inc. v. Cantlon</SOC>
<CITE>2013 ONSC 6312</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 14202</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>Where a gas card is included in a lease, which is signed and discussed with
the lessee, the gas card will not be held as an unsolicited service violating
the CPA. Where a gas card was subject to interest in a lease, where it should
not have been, the lessee is entitled to a refund of the interest paid on the
gas card. Though, where the lessor was not being deliberately deceptive and did
not intentionally structure an unsolicited charge so as to make itself a
concealed profit, it has been held not liable under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 14 of the
CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF>
<SOC>Dalton McPherson and Janett McPherson v. Propane Levac Propane Inc.</SOC>
<JUDGDATE>September 26, 2019</JUDGDATE>
<DOCKET>Doc. 2018-237</DOCKET>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Small Cl. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The plaintiffs cancelled a delivery of propane gas to a rural cottage when
the property turned out to be inaccessible. Despite the cancellation, they were
given an invoice for the delivery of the propane gas. The plaintiffs relied on
s. ^SO2002c30SchA 13 of the CPA which states that &ldquo;a recipient of
unsolicited goods or services has no legal obligation in respect of their use or
disposal&rdquo;. The Small Claims Court held that in this situation, the CPA
provision did not apply as the couple had solicited the goods. As such, there
was no breach of s. ^SO2002c30SchA 13 of the CPA.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="before SO2002c30SchA:14" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>before 14</N>
<TI>Case Law</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 14</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P>We have not included case notes for Part III, with the exception of the few
recent cases set out below. Cases under Part III include numerous prosecutions
for violations by home renovators, landscape companies, home improvement and
service providers. These cases often involve door-to-door sales and behaviour
that is akin to fraud.</P>
<P>These cases usually are decided by their facts and the decisions are not
very interesting, jurisprudentially.</P>
<P><EM>See</EM> https://www.ontario.ca/page/search-consumer-beware-list for
the Ontario government's public information about these cases.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:14" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>14</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 14</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 14</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1908664">
<SOC>Cullaton v. MDG Newmarket Inc.</SOC>
<CITE>2019 ONSC 6432</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 18349</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>A motion for certification of a class action alleging that an HVAC rental
company breached the CPA. The alleged facts are that once the HVAC equipment was
rented, a security interest was put in place against the consumer's property.
This lien was not authorized by the rental agreement (which was &ldquo;misleading
and deceptive&rdquo;) and the &ldquo;buyout program&rdquo; for the equipment
also went undisclosed. Common issues posed by the potential class include breach
of ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 14 and ^SO2002c30SchA 15 of the CPA (unfair practice) as
well as the regulations under the Act regarding leasing, and the direct
agreement requirements in Part IV. The Court also engaged in a summary judgment
analysis on whether the rental agreements were in contravention of the CPA's
requirements and regulations. The Court held that there was a genuine issue for
trial, mainly that Home Trust Company was not necessarily a &ldquo;supplier&rdquo;
under the CPA and the plaintiffs were raising new points of law that could not
be settled without a trial. Partial summary judgment was denied.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1358550">
<SOC>Ramdath v. George Brown College of Applied Arts and Technology</SOC>
<CITE>2012 ONSC 6173</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 14486</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>113 O.R. (3d) 531</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 5389</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>affirmed</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1397517">
<CITE>2013 ONCA 468</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 9183</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<SOC>Ramdath v. Brown (George) College of Applied Arts and Technology</SOC>
<CITE>307 O.A.C. 196</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 3151</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This is a class proceeding. The Court held that the
College committed unfair practices identified in s. ^SO2002c30SchA 14 of the CPA
in two respects. First, it made a false and misleading representation in its
course calendar that the International Business Management program provided
students with the opportunity to complete three industry designations in
addition to the College's graduate certificate. Second, the College represented
that it had &ldquo;approval &hellip; affiliation or connection&rdquo; with
industry associations allowing it to award the industry designations. However,
no such agreements were in place.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1569426">
<SOC>Garg v. Raywal Limited Partnership</SOC>
<CITE>2014 CarswellOnt 15700</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2014] O.J. No. 5335</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The plaintiff claimed damages based on his purchase from the defendant of
kitchen cabinetry which he alleged was unsatisfactory. The Court held that the
mere fact that a claimant is not satisfied or content with the purchased product
or service when properly informed of the matters under discussion and had signed
the contract with open eyes, does not amount to a false, misleading or deceptive
representation under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 14 of CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1701940">
<SOC>1515471 Ontario Inc. v. Davidson</SOC>
<CITE>2016 ONSC 7596</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2016 CarswellOnt 19220</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The plaintiff brought an action for damages regarding the purchase of a
motor vehicle. The Court held that the appellant had engaged in an unfair
practice under the CPA because (1) the appellant failed to provide a bill of
sale at the time of purchase and (2) failed to provide complete details of the
financing, including the total cost of borrowing and rate of interest. The Court
further stated that the absence of a bill of sale or late provision of one,
constitutes a breach by the seller of what was promised to the buyer and that
the breach is an unfair sales practice.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1782977">
<SOC>Jayridge Builders Inc. v. Richard Gerald Draper and Barbara Anne Draper</SOC>
<CITE>2018 ONSC 328</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2018 CarswellOnt 2565</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>89 C.L.R. (4th) 284</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The plaintiff contractor brought an action for damages for breach of
contract and loss of profit for a construction project. The plaintiff claimed
the defendants were informed that the project would take approximately three to
four months to complete, while the defendants claimed that they were told the
project would be completed within eight to twelve weeks. Based on this issue of
scheduling, the defendants' counterclaimed, alleging that the plaintiff engaged
in unfair practice pursuant to s. ^SO2002c30SchA 14 of CPA. The Court dismissed
the counterclaim. The Court stated that the timeline and scheduling
representations were central to the defendants' counterclaim and drew a negative
inference from the fact that one of the defendants, despite being available, had
not testified to corroborate the evidence of the other.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1827989">
<SOC>Richardson v. Samsung</SOC>
<CITE>2018 ONSC 6130</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2018 CarswellOnt 17218</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>affirmed</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1919437">
<CITE>2019 ONSC 6845</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 19400</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The plaintiffs brought a motion before the Court seeking certification as a
class action and alleging that the compensation package provided by Samsung for
its Galaxy Note7 cell phones, which overheated and were recalled, was
inadequate. The Court denied the plaintiffs' motion for certification in part
because the plaintiffs' claim for misrepresentation under ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 14
and ^SO2002c30SchA 17 of the CPA was so broadly and generically pleaded that it
was not possible to discern precisely what was being alleged. In particular, the
pleadings failed to identify when, where, by and to whom, and how the
representation was made. The Court also found that the plaintiffs' claim for
misrepresentation under ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 14 and ^SO2002c30SchA 17 could not
succeed because Samsung, as a manufacturer of the Galaxy Note7 cell phones, is
not a &ldquo;supplier&rdquo; under the CPA. Since the plaintiffs' pleadings did
not include any &ldquo;agreement&rdquo; entered into between the plaintiffs and
Samsung, there is no contractual privity between them and no agreement to
rescind or money to refund under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 18 of the CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1839695">
<SOC>Rebuck v. Ford Motor Company</SOC>
<CITE>2018 ONSC 7405</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2018 CarswellOnt 21593</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The plaintiff alleged that the Ford Motor Company made false, misleading or
deceptive representations to the public regarding the fuel consumption of its
vehicles in violation of ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 14 and ^SO2002c30SchA 17 the CPA. In
the plaintiff's class action certification motion, the Court held that (1)
reliance is not a necessary factor to plead or to establish liability or damages
under the CPA for unfair practices or misrepresentations and (2) courts must
determine whether an impugned representation was untrue, inaccurate or
misleading on an objective basis.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:15" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>15</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 15</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 15</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1728706">
<SOC>Ontario (Ministry of Government and Consumer Services) v. Ivan's Electric
Ltd.</SOC>
<CITE>2017 ONCJ 227</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5064</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>68 B.L.R. (5th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2017] O.J. No. 1707</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This case was decided by a justice of the peace.
Consumers alleged that the defendants excessively overcharged them for
electrical services in the aftermath of an ice storm that left many without
power and electricity. The Court endorsed the Ontario Court of Appeal's approach
in <CASEREF CCDBNUM="88836">
<SOC>Memorial Gardens (Ontario) Ltd. v. Ontario</SOC>
<CITE>1992 CarswellOnt 1059</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>6 O.R. (3d) 720</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>54 O.A.C. 298</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[1992] O.J. No. 98</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>, which takes into consideration the circumstances of a particular
transaction when determining if a supplier committed an unfair practice by
making an unconscionable representation contrary to s. ^SO2002c30SchA 15 of the
CPA. In particular, the Court adopted two of the Court of Appeal's findings: (1)
that the knowledge of the supplier who knew, or ought to have known, that the
price charged grossly exceeded the price at which similar goods or services were
readily available to like customers is not conclusive, but rather, one factor to
consider and (2) there must be evidence to establish that the price charged
exceeded the market price to the level of unconscionability.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:17" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>17</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 17</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 17</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1594711">
<SOC>R. v. Clarke Chevrolet Buick GMC Ltd.</SOC>
<CITE>2015 ONCJ 170</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2015 CarswellOnt 4890</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2015] O.J. No. 1686</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that when there is no <EM>actus reus</EM> on the evidence,
the issue of whether the offence of unconscionable representation contrary to s.
^SO2002c30SchA 17(1) of CPA is a strict liability offence is moot. The Court
further held that the decision of a justice of peace in another case,
characterizing s. ^SO2002c30SchA 17(1) as an objective <EM>mens rea</EM>
offence does not operate to bind subsequent decisions.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1728706">
<SOC>Ontario (Ministry of Government and Consumer Services) v. Ivan's Electric
Ltd.</SOC>
<CITE>2017 ONCJ 227</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5064</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>68 B.L.R. (5th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2017] O.J. No. 1707</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This case was decided by a justice of the peace. The
Court held that the following could constitute unfair practices under ss.
^SO2002c30SchA 14&ndash;17 of the CPA depending on the circumstances: (a)
grossly overcharging consumers; (b) omitting to inform consumers of significant
charges (e.g. emergency service calls or charges for attending a consumer's
residence); (c) charging the consumer a cancellation fee in a direct agreement
although the CPA prohibits that practice; (d) omitting to inform consumers of
material facts (e.g. that a company is no longer able to provide the service and
will pass on the work to another company); and (e) failing to inform the
consumer of additional work or material not covered in the first direct
agreement, particularly when the supplier has not provided the consumer with a
detailed cost breakdown.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1827989">
<SOC>Richardson v. Samsung</SOC>
<CITE>2018 ONSC 6130</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2018 CarswellOnt 17218</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>affirmed</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1919437">
<CITE>2019 ONSC 6845</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 19400</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The plaintiffs brought a motion before the Court seeking certification as a
class action and alleging that the compensation package provided by Samsung for
its Galaxy Note7 cell phones, which overheated and were recalled, was
inadequate. The Court denied the plaintiffs' motion for certification in part
because the plaintiffs' claim for misrepresentation under ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 14
and ^SO2002c30SchA 17 of the CPA was so broadly and generically pleaded that it
was not possible to discern precisely what was being alleged. In particular, the
pleadings failed to identify when, where, by and to whom, and how the
representation was made. The Court also found that the plaintiffs' claim for
misrepresentation under ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 14 and ^SO2002c30SchA 17 could not
succeed because Samsung, as a manufacturer of the Galaxy Note7 cell phones, is
not a &ldquo;supplier&rdquo; under the CPA. Since the plaintiffs' pleadings did
not include any &ldquo;agreement&rdquo; entered into between the plaintiffs and
Samsung, there is no contractual privity between them and no agreement to
rescind or money to refund under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 18 of the CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1839695">
<SOC>Rebuck v. Ford Motor Company</SOC>
<CITE>2018 ONSC 7405</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2018 CarswellOnt 21593</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The plaintiff alleged that the Ford Motor Company made false, misleading or
deceptive representations to the public regarding the fuel consumption of its
vehicles in violation of ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 14 and ^SO2002c30SchA 17 the CPA. In
the plaintiff's class action certification motion, the Court held that (1)
reliance is not a necessary factor to plead or to establish liability or damages
under the CPA for unfair practices or misrepresentations and (2) courts must
determine whether an impugned representation was untrue, inaccurate or
misleading on an objective basis.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1868224">
<SOC>Bernstein v. Peoples Trust Company</SOC>
<CITE>2019 ONSC 2867</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 7328</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1884293">
<CITE>2019 ONSC 4675</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 12825</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1901101">
<CITE>2019 ONSC 6076</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 17202</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This is a class proceeding. The Court found that Peoples
Trust Company engaged in unfair practices or misrepresentations contrary to ss.
^SO2002c30SchA 14&ndash;17 of the CPA because (1) no additional fees were
apparent to purchasers of Peoples Trust Company's Single Load Prepaid Cards (&ldquo;SLP
cards&rdquo;) by looking at the retail display (i.e. external packaging) except
for the application fee, (2) nothing on the external packaging or face of the
SLP cards warns of the consequences of expiry, (3) not all fees are disclosed by
Peoples Trust Company on their SLP cards, and (4) Peoples Trust Company's
cardholder agreements mislead consumers about their rights to expired balances.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:18(1)" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>18(1)</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 18(1)</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 18(1)</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1358550">
<SOC>Ramdath v. George Brown College of Applied Arts and Technology</SOC>
<CITE>2012 ONSC 6173</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 14486</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>113 O.R. (3d) 531</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 5389</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>affirmed</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1397517">
<CITE>2013 ONCA 468</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 9183</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<SOC>Ramdath v. Brown (George) College of Applied Arts and Technology</SOC>
<CITE>307 O.A.C. 196</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 3151</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This is a class proceeding. The Court held that
consumers do not need to provide that they relied on the representation
constituting the unfair practice or that the representation induced the consumer
to enter into the agreement for the purposes of seeking rescission or a remedy
under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 18 of the CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1497682">
<SOC>Sankar v. Bell Mobility Inc.</SOC>
<CITE>2013 ONSC 5916</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 13796</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>52 C.P.C. (7th) 75</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 4503</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1504052">
<CITE>2013 ONSC 6886</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 15481</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>52 C.P.C. (7th) 111</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>leave to appeal refused</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1515678">
<CITE>2013 ONSC 7529</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 18414</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>Where a vendor and consumer do not make an agreement &ldquo;after or while&rdquo;
the vendor has engaged in an unfair practice, it will not be held to have
engaged in unfair practices under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 18. The &ldquo;Unfair
Practices&rdquo; section is concerned with representations inducing a consumer
agreement and the protection of consumers who may otherwise enter agreements
based on deceptive or unconscionable representations. A consumer who signed an
agreement, without the presence of a deceptive or unconscionable representation,
but while the vendor was making deceptive or unconscionable representations to
others, cannot advance a claim for relief under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 18(1).</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
