<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1901101">
<CITE>2019 ONSC 6076</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 17202</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This is a class proceeding. Peoples Trust Company argued
that Bernstein, the representative plaintiff, violated the notice requirement in
s. ^SO2002c30SchA 18(3) of the CPA because she brought her claim more than a
year after receiving her Peoples Trust Company payment card. However, the Court
waived the notice requirement using its broad discretion in s. ^SO2002c30SchA
101 because it was in the interests of justice for two reasons. First, the Court
found that the waiver was superfluous in this case because the notice
requirement is not a precondition to either bringing an action under s.
^SO2002c30SchA 100 of the CPA or demanding a refund from a supplier who has
charged illegal fees on open loop gift cards contrary to O. Reg. 17/05. In
addition, there is no notice requirement for a common law action for breach of
contract or for unjust enrichment, both of which the class members successfully
brought before the Court. Second, to allow Peoples Trust Company to use the
notice requirement in s. ^SO2002c30SchA 18(3) as a shield after class members
have demonstrated that they have viable claims would inhibit access to justice.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
