<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1728706">
<SOC>Ontario (Ministry of Government and Consumer Services) v. Ivan's Electric
Ltd.</SOC>
<CITE>2017 ONCJ 227</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5064</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>68 B.L.R. (5th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2017] O.J. No. 1707</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This case was decided by a justice of the peace.
Consumers alleged that the defendants excessively overcharged them for
electrical services in the aftermath of an ice storm that left many without
power and electricity. The defendants argued that the agreements they entered
into with consumers were not direct agreements within the meaning of the CPA.
The Court held that the definition of &ldquo;direct agreement&rdquo; in s.
^SO2002c30SchA 20(1) includes agreements entered into at consumers' residences
or dwellings regardless of who solicited the transaction. In other words, direct
agreements are not limited to situations where door-to-door salespersons solicit
consumers to enter into agreements for goods or services; they also include
situations where consumers solicit suppliers for goods or services. The key
consideration is where the agreement takes place, not who contacted who first.</P>
<BLOCK2>
<TI>Case Law: Reg. Section 42(2)</TI>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1282618">
<SOC>Weller v. Reliance Home Comfort Ltd. Partnership</SOC>
<CITE>2012 ONCA 360</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 6714</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>110 O.R. (3d) 743</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>350 D.L.R. (4th) 301</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>291 O.A.C. 388</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 2415</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The supplier unilaterally amended the consumer agreement, but failed to
comply with s. ^OReg17/05 42(2)2 of O. Reg. 17/05 because it did not give the
consumer the right to retain the existing agreement unchanged or the right to
terminate the amended agreement. In particular, the Court held that if a
consumer is given the right to terminate as an alternative to accepting an
amended, renewed or extended consumer agreement as per s. ^OReg17/05 42(2)2,
such right must be unconditional. An agreement that attaches conditions to the
right to terminate does not provide the consumer with a true alternative to
accepting the amendment. The two conditions imposed by the supplier that
violated s. ^OReg17/05 42(2)2 were that in order to terminate (1) the consumer
must not be in default under the agreement and (2) the consumer must pay the
standard removal charges.</P>
</BLOCK2>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
