</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This is a class proceeding. The Court held that Peoples
Trust Company's Single Load Prepaid Cards (&ldquo;SLP cards&rdquo;) are not a
financial product exempt under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 2(2)(c) from the operation of
the CPA because they were marketed as gifts, which by their nature are generally
intended for personal purposes. Instead, the Court found that the SLP cards are
open loop gift cards regulated by O. Reg. 17/05 and indistinguishable from mall
cards. In contrast, the Court held that Peoples Trust Company's General Purpose
Reloadable Prepaid Cards (&ldquo;GPR cards&rdquo;) are a financial product
exempt from the CPA by virtue of s. ^SO2002c30SchA 2(2)(c) because through the
means of access to a payment network, the end of GPR cards is banking.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1868224">
<SOC>Bernstein v. Peoples Trust Company</SOC>
<CITE>2019 ONSC 2867</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 7328</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1884293">
<CITE>2019 ONSC 4675</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 12825</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
