</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This is a class proceeding. The Court held that there is
no actual gifting requirement in an open loop gift card agreement. Through its
analysis of legislative history, the Court concluded that the Government of
Ontario never intended that gifting be a prerequisite to the protection provided
to consumers by O. Reg. 17/05. In addition, the Court found that there is no
requirement that the card entitle the holder to purchase any specific good or
service. Rather, the term &ldquo;entitlement&rdquo; in the &ldquo;open loop gift
card agreement&rdquo; definition is an entitlement to &ldquo;apply&rdquo; the
voucher towards goods and services &ldquo;from multiple unaffiliated sellers.&rdquo;</P>
