<TI>Case Law: Section 22</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 22</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1241399">
<SOC>Ontario (Ministry of Consumer Services) v. K-Tech Building Systems Inc.</SOC>
<CITE>2012 ONCJ 219</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 4865</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>13 C.L.R. (4th) 187</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 1764</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This case was decided by a justice of the peace. The
Court held that the defendants engaged to construct a cottage failed to deliver
a future performance agreement containing information required by s. ^OReg17/05
24 of O. Reg. 17/05 and contrary to s. ^SO2002c30SchA 22 of the CPA.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1155619">
<SOC>Graham v. Imperial Parking Canada Corp.</SOC>
<CITE>2010 ONSC 4982</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2010 CarswellOnt 6941</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>74 B.L.R. (4th) 172</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2010] O.J. No. 3898</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>leave to appeal refused</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1185798">
<CITE>2011 ONSC 991</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2011 CarswellOnt 3282</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>85 B.L.R. (4th) 167</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>279 O.A.C. 342</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2011] O.J. No. 2027</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that the CPA does not govern all cases of consumer agreements
and that parking agreements are not future performance agreements.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1379998">
<SOC>Connect Electric Inc. v. Pullen</SOC>
<CITE>2013 ONSC 1837</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 3634</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 1464</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>.</P>
<P>The Court held that an oral future performance agreement was illegal as it
was not in writing and thus not in compliance with s. ^SO2002c30SchA 22 of the
CPA. However, the Court ruled that s. ^SO2002c30SchA 93(2) of the Act applied in
these circumstances as it would have been inequitable not to hold defendants
bound by oral agreement.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1432287">
<SOC>Grainger v. Flaska</SOC>
<CITE>2013 ONSC 4863</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 11171</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>18 B.L.R. (5th) 253</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>31 C.L.R. (4th) 23</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The general purpose of the CPA is to protect consumers; however, it can also
work to protect suppliers who are being taken advantage of by deceitful
consumers. Where a homeowner refuses to pay a contractor on the basis that there
is no written contract between the parties, and it is beyond doubt that both
parties knew and understood the terms of the contract, the Court has the
jurisdiction, under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 93(2) of the Act, to order a consumer
bound by the agreement between the parties. Relevant factors to consider when
determining whether a consumer should be bound by an agreement not in accordance
with the Act include: 
<P1>a. the seriousness of the consequences of invalidating the contract;</P1> 
<P1>b. the social utility of those consequences;</P1> 
<P1>c. the class of persons for whom the prohibition was enacted, whether the
contract was bargained for at arm's length;</P1> 
<P1>d. whether the consumer was unfairly taken advantage of, whether the
agreement was wholly or substantially completed;</P1> 
<P1>e. the degree of benefit derived by the consumer; and</P1> 
<P1>f. and whether it would be inherently wrong or contrary to public policy to
enforce the contract.</P1></P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1716067">
<SOC>Bernstein v. Peoples Trust Co.</SOC>
<CITE>2017 ONSC 752</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 1361</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>97 C.P.C. (7th) 286</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1729471">
<CITE>2017 ONSC 2189</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5120</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that it was not plain and obvious that prepaid payment cards
were not subject to the Act.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:26" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>26</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 26</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 26</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="985822">
<SOC>FM Industries v. Tomasevic</SOC>
<CITE>2007 CarswellOnt 1842</CITE>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court ruled by interpreting s. ^SO2002c30SchA 26(4) of the CPA that a
failure to complete a future performance agreement because of the actions of the
&ldquo;consumer&rdquo; would entitle the &ldquo;supplier&rdquo; to relief by way
of damages.</P>
<BLOCK2>
<TI>Case Law: Reg. Sections 25.1&ndash;25.5</TI>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1658938">
<SOC>Sankar v. Bell Mobility Inc.</SOC>
<CITE>2016 ONCA 242</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2016 CarswellOnt 4940</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>400 D.L.R. (4th) 637</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>348 O.A.C. 58</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>affirmed</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1729512">
<CITE>2017 ONCA 295</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5104</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>1 C.P.C. (8th) 369</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>410 D.L.R. (4th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>leave to appeal refused</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1761823">
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 16212</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 16213</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2016] S.C.C.A. No. 251</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The gift card regulations found in O. Reg 17/05 do not apply to prepaid
phone cards. The purpose of these regulations is to prevent the expiry of an
agreement before the seller of the card has delivered the goods or performed the
services promised under the agreement. They do not prohibit an agreement being
time-limited. The fact that the service purchased was for a defined period of
wireless service, calculated on the dollar value of credits the consumer added
to the account, was not a breach of the regulations, as concluding otherwise
would mean that Bell was required to keep the wireless service and number
available to the customer indefinitely, a patently unreasonable outcome.
Informing this decision was the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications
Commission's decision to decline to require service providers to permit
consumers to carry over their prepaid unused minutes indefinitely, choosing to
require a 7-day grace period instead (which Bell adopted in its agreements). In
view of these findings, it was not necessary to decide whether the Regulation
applies only to gift cards purchased as gifts, or whether the case fell within
the single service exception.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1868224">
<SOC>Bernstein v. Peoples Trust Company</SOC>
<CITE>2019 ONSC 2867</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 7328</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1884293">
<CITE>2019 ONSC 4675</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 12825</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1901101">
<CITE>2019 ONSC 6076</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 17202</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This is a class proceeding. The Court held that Peoples
Trust Company's payment cards are not &ldquo;single service&rdquo; cards
exempted from the operation of O. Reg. 17/05 by s. 25.1(1)(b) of the Regulation.
The exemption in s. 25.1(1)(b) was intended to provide an exception regarding
expiry dates in gift cards for single good or service businesses (e.g. haircut,
manicure, massage, etc.). However, Peoples Trust Company offers a variety of
services in relation to its payment cards and consumers can use its payment
cards to access many different goods and services.</P>
<P>The Court held that Peoples Trust Company violated s. ^OReg17/05 25.3 of O.
Reg 17/05 by imposing &ldquo;valid thru dates&rdquo; (i.e. expiry dates) on its
Single Load Prepaid Cards (&ldquo;SLP cards&rdquo;) and retaining consumers'
balances on its SLP cards through &ldquo;cancellation fees&rdquo; after they had
expired.</P>
<P>The Court held that Peoples Trust Company violated s. ^OReg17/05 25.4 of O.
Reg 17/05 by charging an &ldquo;activation fee&rdquo; greater than $2.50 and
dormancy fees/monthly fees earlier than the 15th month after activation on its
SLP cards.</P>
</BLOCK2>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:35" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>35</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 35</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 35</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1295948">
<SOC>Wilson v. Semon</SOC>
<CITE>2011 CarswellOnt 15953</CITE>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>affirmed</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1295827">
<CITE>2012 ONCA 558</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 10364</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that it is required that a personal development services
agreement contain statements which would advise the &ldquo;consumer&rdquo; of
his or her right to terminate the contract within a 10-day period. In the
absence of such statements, a one-year period to terminate would apply.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:43.1" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>43.1</N>
<TI>Case Law: Reg. Section 83</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 43.1</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1728706">
<SOC>Ontario (Ministry of Government and Consumer Services) v. Ivan's Electric
Ltd.</SOC>
<CITE>2017 ONCJ 227</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5064</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>68 B.L.R. (5th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2017] O.J. No. 1707</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This case was decided by a justice of the peace.
Consumers alleged that the defendants excessively overcharged them for
electrical services in the aftermath of an ice storm that left many without
power and electricity. Where consumers cancelled their direct agreements under
s. ^SO2002c30SchA 43 of the CPA, the Court held that the defendants (i.e.
suppliers) could not deduct as reasonable compensation under s. ^OReg17/05 83 of
O. Reg. 17/05 a 2% credit card service fee, a minimum labour cost or a minimum
pick up and return of parts cost because the consumers had not agreed to receive
these goods or services under the direct agreements.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:45" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>45</N>
<TI>Case Law: Sections 45&ndash;47</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 45</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1117421">
<SOC>Singer v. Schering-Plough Canada Inc.</SOC>
<CITE>2010 ONSC 42</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2010 CarswellOnt 79</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>87 C.P.C. (6th) 276</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2010] O.J. No. 113</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1129585">
<CITE>2010 ONSC 1737</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2010 CarswellOnt 1820</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>87 C.P.C. (6th) 345</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2010] O.J. No. 1243</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
