<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:48" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>48</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 48</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 48</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1052896">
<SOC>Elliott v. Lyons Auto Body Ltd.</SOC>
<CITE>2008 CarswellOnt 5235</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>52 B.L.R. (4th) 157</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>14 P.P.S.A.C. (3d) 187</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that a repair shop was not entitled to assert a lien on the
car, as the written estimate of the total cost of repairs to a vehicle and the
information that should have been set out under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 48 of the CPA
was not complied with.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="before SO2002c30SchA:55" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>before 55</N>
<TI>Case Law</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 55</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P>There is a significant number of cases involving motor vehicle repair issues
under Part VI of the CPA. We have not summarized them here (other than a few)
because we believe that users of this publication have little or no need for
such case law. In any event, like Part III cases, these turn on their facts in
most cases&mdash;they are not particularly interesting as jurisprudence.</P>
<P>The interplay between the CPA and the <EM>Repair and Storage Liens Act</EM>
(RSLA) should be noted. A failure to comply with the CPA may eliminate lien
rights under the RSLA. See:</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1933707">
<SOC>2200334 Ontario Inc. v. Landmark Vehicle Leasing Corp.</SOC>
<CITE>2019 ONSC 7532</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 21114</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>11 P.P.S.A.C. (4th) 273</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>Whether the plaintiff, Toronto Motorsports Park (TMP), was required to
comply with ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 56, ^SO2002c30SchA 57, ^SO2002c30SchA 58(1) and
^SO2002c30SchA 59 (Motor Vehicle Repairs) of the CPA and failure to do so would
trigger the provision of the RSLA that declares that no repairer's lien arises
if these provisions of the CPA are not complied with. The vehicle was leased to
a corporation for use by that corporation's president. The individual arranged
for the repair work on the vehicle, a Ferrari. The Court held that when TMP
undertook to repair the Ferrari, the person requesting the repairs was doing so
as president of a corporation, not in a personal capacity. Therefore, the CPA
did not apply to this transaction.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1997545">
<SOC>Kew v. Konarski</SOC>
<CITE>2020 ONSC 4677</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2020 CarswellOnt 11052</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The CPA is cited in this case for its intersection with the RSLA. However,
the Court's judgment focuses on the RSLA rather than the CPA. The Court held
that even if Konarski had a consumer agreement, no estimate for car storage
services was given to the consumer in contravention of s. ^SO2002c30SchA 56(1)
of the CPA nor did any exception under s. 56(2) apply to the situation.
Moreover, no written agreement was signed (against s. 58(1) and s. 59 prescribed
regulations). This case arose from a dispute between the widow of a vehicle
owner and the deceased man's friend who stored a number of vehicles&mdash;either
as a favour or for payment. The case turns on the impact of certain features to
follow the CPA on rights under the RSLA. The widow was held to be a &ldquo;consumer&rdquo;
in her dealings with the repairer/storer; no written estimates were provided for
repairs; no proper disclosure of the contract was made (CPA s. ^SO2002c30SchA
56(1)); therefore no lien rights for repairs could be asserted. The Court found
the defendant to be a repairer and not a storer.</P>
<P><CASEREF>
<SOC>Memory Lane Restorations and Collectables Ltd. v. James Turple</SOC>
<JUDGDATE>April 28, 2020</JUDGDATE>
<DOCKET>Doc. 184/19</DOCKET>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Small Cl. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>This case deals with Part VI of the CPA. Under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 56(1),
&ldquo;no repairer shall charge a consumer for any work or repairs unless the
repairer first gives the consumer an estimate that meets the prescribed
requirements&rdquo;. The plaintiff argued that the company was not subject to
the CPA because it was not a &ldquo;repairer&rdquo; but a &ldquo;restorer&rdquo;
of vehicles. The Court disagreed and found that the company was a repairer and
subject to the CPA as &ldquo;restore&rdquo; and &ldquo;repair&rdquo; are used
interchangeably. Despite the contract for repainting the car not being made in
accordance with the CPA (s. ^SO2002c30SchA 93(1)), the Court found it would be
inequitable for the defendant not to be bound to the agreement (s.
^SO2002c30SchA 93(2)).</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:56" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>56</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 56</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 56</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="2006470">
<SOC>1179640 Ontario Limited v. DaSilva</SOC>
<CITE>2020 ONSC 5456</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2020 CarswellOnt 12976</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>64 M.V.R. (7th) 219</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>A Divisional Court appeal from a Small Claims Court decision held that
consumer approval to motor vehicle repairs cannot rely on yet undetermined
details (not yet provided to the consumer), and that an insurer does not have
the authority to authorize repairs on behalf of the consumer.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:59" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>59</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 59</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 59</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1167279">
<SOC>407 Auto Collision v. Bounsanga</SOC>
<CITE>2010 CarswellOnt 9598</CITE>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that when an authorization for repairs is not in writing,
then compliance with s. ^OReg17/05 49 of the O. Reg. 17/05 is required. <EM>See
also</EM>: <CASEREF CCDBNUM="1138741">
<SOC>Gary Auto Repair v. Velke</SOC>
<CITE>2010 ONSC 3183</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2010 CarswellOnt 3758</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>263 O.A.C. 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:61" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>61</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 61</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 61</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1201397">
<SOC>Horizon Custom Cycles v. Lefurgey</SOC>
<CITE>2011 ONSC 5168</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2011 CarswellOnt 8974</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court allowed the defendant an additional deduction for parts that were
not returned, as the plaintiff, as a repairer, had an obligation to return all
parts pursuant to s. ^SO2002c30SchA 61 of the CPA.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:68" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>68</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 68</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 68</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1067495">
<SOC>Royal Bank v. Lau</SOC>
<CITE>2008 CarswellOnt 7438</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2008] O.J. No. 5007</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1071774">
<CITE>2009 CarswellOnt 144</CITE>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court ruled in favour of the plaintiff for a credit card debt owed by
the defendant by virtue of s. ^SO2002c30SchA 68(1) of the CPA, as it deems a
user of a credit card to have entered into a credit agreement. See also:
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1386885">
<SOC>Royal Bank of Canada v. Raincock</SOC>
<CITE>2013 ONSC 2876</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 5915</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 2216</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1869982">
<SOC>Royal Bank of Canada v. Pady</SOC>
<CITE>2019 ONSC 3095</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 7785</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>.</P>
<P>The defendant was a co-applicant on a credit card issued by the Royal Bank
of Canada (RBC). The RBC brought a motion for summary judgment, seeking payment
of the balance owing on the credit card. The Court held that s. ^SO2002c30SchA
68(1) of the CPA makes it clear that once a consumer uses a credit card, they
are deemed to have entered into a credit agreement with the issuer of the card.
Therefore, although the defendant did not apply for the credit card, she agreed
to the terms of the credit agreement with RBC by virtue of using the card.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:89" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
