<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The deputy judge held that the vehicle lease agreement did not bind the
defendant, as the same was not in compliance with O. Reg. 17/05 read with s.
^SO2002c30SchA 89 of the CPA. Further, s. ^SO2002c30SchA 93(1) of the CPA
relieves a consumer of any liability under a consumer agreement unless it was
prepared in accordance with the Act and its Regulations. On appeal, the
Appellate Court found that the plaintiff did provide a written lease disclosure
form that formed part of the vehicle lease agreement as required by O. Reg.
17/05. Because the lease disclosure form was signed and initiated by the
defendant and the calculations of amounts owing and capitalized payments under
the lease were clear, the Appellate Court held that subject to a gas card issue,
the plaintiff complied with its disclosure requirements under s. ^SO2002c30SchA
89 of the CPA. <EM>See also</EM>: <CASEREF>
<SOC>Action Auto Leasing &amp; Gallery Inc. v. Crawford</SOC>
