<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:92" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>92</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 92</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 92</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1241399">
<SOC>Ontario (Ministry of Consumer Services) v. K-Tech Building Systems Inc.</SOC>
<CITE>2012 ONCJ 219</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 4865</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>13 C.L.R. (4th) 187</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 1764</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This case was decided by a justice of the peace. The
Court held that the notice requirements under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 92 of the CPA
for cancellation of the contract were complied with by the plaintiff.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1728706">
<SOC>Ontario (Ministry of Government and Consumer Services) v. Ivan's Electric
Ltd.</SOC>
<CITE>2017 ONCJ 227</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5064</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>68 B.L.R. (5th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2017] O.J. No. 1707</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This case was decided by a justice of the peace.
Consumers alleged that the defendants excessively overcharged them for
electrical services in the aftermath of an ice storm that left many without
power and electricity. The Court found that a verbal demand for cancellation, a
direct request to the supplier for a refund, an indirect request for a refund
through the Better Business Bureau or a consumer's request to their credit card
company to reverse charges on their credit card relating to the impugned
transaction with the supplier are all sufficient means to give notice of
cancellation under ss. ^SO2002c30SchA 92 and ^SO2002c30SchA 94 of the CPA.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:93" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>93</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 93</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 93</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1673539">
<SOC>Lexfund Inc. v. Ferro</SOC>
<CITE>2016 ONSC 4113</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2016 CarswellOnt 9941</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>Looking to realize on loans made to the defendant borrowers, the plaintiff
lender is found to have breached the Act in several ways with the main breach
being that it did not forward any disclosure whatsoever to the borrowers as
legislated by the Act. Despite the application of s. 70 which mandated that the
defendents pay no interest, s. 93 was applied to allow the judge to set an
interest rate of 5%, as it would be inequitable for the defendants not to pay
any interest for their loans which allowed them to prosecute their motor vehicle
accident cases, all of which resulted in recoveries for the borrowers. Also, the
defendants would have known that they were not getting the use of the money
interest free.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1668245">
<SOC>Tecton Construction Inc. v. Yeung</SOC>
<CITE>2016 ONSC 3039</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2016 CarswellOnt 8090</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>68 C.L.R. (4th) 327</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>A clause in a contract that required changes to be in writing did not
preclude a home renovator's claims for compensation for work agreed to orally.
This clause was found to apply to all renovation work completed, whether within
the scope of the written contract or not, based on the provision (s. 11) that
any ambiguity should be resolved in favour of the defendant homeowners. However,
the Court ordered that the consumer is bound by the agreement because it would
be inequitable for the consumer not to be bound, as per s. ^SO2002c30SchA 93(2).
It would have been inequitable for the defendant homeowners to receive the
benefit of the invoiced items without paying for them.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1379998">
<SOC>Connect Electric Inc. v. Pullen</SOC>
<CITE>2013 ONSC 1837</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 3634</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2013] O.J. No. 1464</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The plaintiff entered into an oral agreement for performance of electrical
work without complying with s. ^SO2002c30SchA 22 of the CPA and thus rendering
the contract invalid. The Court, by applying s. ^SO2002c30SchA 93(2) of the CPA,
granted relief by holding that it would have been inequitable not to hold the
defendants bound by the oral agreement.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1432287">
<SOC>Grainger v. Flaska</SOC>
<CITE>2013 ONSC 4863</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 11171</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>18 B.L.R. (5th) 253</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>31 C.L.R. (4th) 23</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The general purpose of the CPA is to protect consumers; however, it can also
work to protect suppliers who are being taken advantage of by deceitful
consumers. Where a homeowner refuses to pay a contractor on the basis that there
is no written contract between the parties, and it is beyond doubt that both
parties knew and understood the terms of the contract, the Court has the
jurisdiction, under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 93(2) of the Act, to order a consumer
bound by the agreement between the parties. Relevant factors to consider when
determining whether a consumer should be bound by an agreement not in accordance
with the Act include: 
<P1>a. the seriousness of the consequences of invalidating the contract;</P1> 
<P1>b. the social utility of those consequences;</P1> 
<P1>c. the class of persons for whom the prohibition was enacted;</P1> 
<P1>d. whether the contract was bargained for at arm's length;</P1> 
<P1>e. whether the consumer was unfairly taken advantage of;</P1> 
<P1>f. whether the agreement was wholly or substantially completed</P1> 
<P1>g. the degree of benefit derived by the consumer, and;</P1> 
<P1>h. whether it would be inherently wrong or contrary to public policy to
enforce the contract.</P1></P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1282618">
<SOC>Weller v. Reliance Home Comfort Ltd. Partnership</SOC>
<CITE>2012 ONCA 360</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 6714</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>110 O.R. (3d) 743</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>350 D.L.R. (4th) 301</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>291 O.A.C. 388</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 2415</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>The Court held that s. ^SO2002c30SchA 93(2) of the CPA applied even though
the consumer was not attempting to resile from the entire agreement, only the
amendment made by the supplier. The Court found that the wording &ldquo;all or a
portion or portions of a consumer agreement&rdquo; in s. ^SO2002c30SchA 93(2) is
broad enough to include an amendment to an agreement. In addition, the Court
held that the test for applying s. ^SO2002c30SchA 93(2) is not the nature of the
non-compliance, but rather, whether it would be inequitable for a consumer not
to be bound by the amendment. Nonetheless, consideration of the nature of the
non-compliance remains a factor because the greater the deviation from the
legislative scheme, the more likely that a court will find that it would not be
inequitable for a consumer not to be bound by the amendment. In this case, the
Court held that it would be inequitable for the consumer not to be bound by the
supplier's amendment because the amendment does not prejudice the consumer and
the consumer brought the application for a collateral purpose.</P>
<P><CASEREF>
<SOC>Memory Lane Restorations and Collectables Ltd. v. James Turple</SOC>
<JUDGDATE>April 28, 2020</JUDGDATE>
<DOCKET>Doc. 184/19</DOCKET>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Small Cl. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>This case deals with Part VI of the CPA. Under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 56(1)
&ldquo;no repairer shall charge a consumer for any work or repairs unless the
repairer first gives the consumer an estimate that meets the prescribed
requirements&rdquo;. The plaintiff argued that the company was not subject to
the CPA because they were not a &ldquo;repairer&rdquo; but a &ldquo;restorer&rdquo;
of vehicles. The court disagreed and found that the company was a repairer and
subject to the CPA as &ldquo;restore&rdquo; and &ldquo;repair&rdquo; are used
interchangeably. Despite the contract for repainting the car not being made in
accordance with the CPA (s. ^SO2002c30SchA 93(1)), the Court found it would be
inequitable for the defendant not to be bound to the agreement (s.
^SO2002c30SchA 93(2)).</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="2025320">
<SOC>Taurus Auto v. Zhou</SOC>
<CITE>2020 ONSC 7127</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2020 CarswellOnt 19120</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>Appeal from small claims decision dismissing auto repairer's claim for
repairs. Deputy judge found that the consumer had not authorized repairs and
thus there was no agreement between the parties. Repairer argued that it should
be compensated on a <EM>quantum meruit</EM> basis, under s. ^SO2002c30SchA 93
of the CPA. Repairer denied payment of any sum for repairs or storage; it lacked
&ldquo;clean hands&rdquo;. Implication in Divisional Court that rampant fraud in
the towing and repair industry was relevant factor. Appeal dismissed.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
