<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:96" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>96</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 96</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 96</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1241399">
<SOC>Ontario (Ministry of Consumer Services) v. K-Tech Building Systems Inc.</SOC>
<CITE>2012 ONCJ 219</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 4865</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>13 C.L.R. (4th) 187</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] O.J. No. 1764</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This case was decided by a justice of the peace. The
Court held that the defendants failed to provide a refund within 15 days of
notice of cancellation of consumer agreement as required by s. ^SO2002c30SchA
96(1) of the CPA and s. ^OReg17/05 79(1) of O. Reg. 17/05.</P>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1728706">
<SOC>Ontario (Ministry of Government and Consumer Services) v. Ivan's Electric
Ltd.</SOC>
<CITE>2017 ONCJ 227</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5064</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>68 B.L.R. (5th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2017] O.J. No. 1707</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This case was decided by a justice of the peace.
Consumers alleged that the defendants excessively overcharged them for
electrical services in the aftermath of an ice storm that left many without
power and electricity. The Court held that 11 agreements between consumers and
the defendants were direct agreements within the meaning of the CPA and s.
^SO2002c30SchA 96(1) obligated the defendants to refund any payments provided by
consumers under these agreements, such as the 30% deposit fee, because the
defendants were not legally entitled to ask consumers for such payments. The
Court further held that a supplier's refund obligation is automatic and does not
require a former demand for the refund. In other words, once consumers notified
the defendants that they were cancelling the direct agreements, the defendants
were obligated under ss. ^OReg17/05 79(1) and ^OReg17/05 80(1) of O. Reg. 17/05
to refund any payment made by the consumers under the direct agreements
regardless of whether the consumers had actually requested a refund.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:100" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>100</N>
<TI>Case Law: Sections 100 and 101</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 100</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1868224">
<SOC>Bernstein v. Peoples Trust Company</SOC>
<CITE>2019 ONSC 2867</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 7328</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1884293">
<CITE>2019 ONSC 4675</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 12825</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
<CASEHIST>
<CASEDISP>additional reasons</CASEDISP>
<CASEREF CCDBNUM="1901101">
<CITE>2019 ONSC 6076</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 17202</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF>
</CASEHIST>
</CASEREF></P>
<P><BOLD>Note:</BOLD> This is a class proceeding. Peoples Trust Company argued
that Bernstein, the representative plaintiff, violated the notice requirement in
s. ^SO2002c30SchA 18(3) of the CPA because she brought her claim more than a
year after receiving her Peoples Trust Company payment card. However, the Court
waived the notice requirement using its broad discretion in s. ^SO2002c30SchA
101 because it was in the interests of justice for two reasons. First, the Court
found that the waiver was superfluous in this case because the notice
requirement is not a precondition to either bringing an action under s.
^SO2002c30SchA 100 of the CPA or demanding a refund from a supplier who has
charged illegal fees on open loop gift cards contrary to O. Reg. 17/05. In
addition, there is no notice requirement for a common law action for breach of
contract or for unjust enrichment, both of which the class members successfully
brought before the Court. Second, to allow Peoples Trust Company to use the
notice requirement in s. ^SO2002c30SchA 18(3) as a shield after class members
have demonstrated that they have viable claims would inhibit access to justice.</P>
<P>In its decision to award punitive damages, the Court endorsed the principles
articulated by the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF CCDBNUM="1228877">
<SOC>Richard c. Time Inc.</SOC>
<CITE>2012 SCC 8</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellQue 1218</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2012 CarswellQue 1219</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] 1 S.C.R. 265</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<SOC>Time inc. v. Richard</SOC>
<CITE>342 D.L.R. (4th) 1</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>427 N.R. 203</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>[2012] S.C.J. No. 8</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>, and <CASEREF CCDBNUM="1559328">
<SOC>Marcotte c. Banque de Montr&eacute;al</SOC>
<CITE>2014 CSC 55</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2014 SCC 55</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2014 CarswellQue 9001</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2014 CarswellQue 9002</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<SOC>Bank of Montreal v. Marcotte</SOC>
<CITE>[2014] 2 S.C.R. 725</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>25 B.L.R. (5th) 173</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>374 D.L.R. (4th) 581</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>462 N.R. 202</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF>. These include: 
<P1>a. Punitive damages for a violation of consumer protection legislation must
have the purpose of discouraging the repetition of undesirable conduct and may
only be awarded in light of: (a) intentional, malicious or vexatious violations
of the legislation; or (b) conduct that displays ignorance, carelessness or
serious negligence assessed in light of the merchant's conduct both before and
after the violation.</P1> 
<P1>b. While punitive damages may be awarded under consumer protection statute
when the merchant's conduct is malicious, oppressive, high-handed or a marked
departure from ordinary standards of decency, which is a requirement for
punitive damages under the common law, such conduct is not a prerequisite for an
award of punitive damages under the consumer protection statute.</P1> 
<P1>c. The fact that in a class action, the award of damages may in and of
itself have a preventative and deterrent effect does not impose a higher
threshold for awarding punitive damages, and the amount of the class action
award is not a factor in the legal test for the determination of punitive
damages for the class members.</P1> 
<P1>d. Neither evidence of antisocial behaviour nor reprehensible conduct is
required to award punitive damages; rather, what is necessary is an examination
of the overall conduct of the merchant, before, during and after the violation,
for behaviour that was: (a) lax, passive or ignorant with respect to consumers'
rights and to their own obligations; or (b) conduct that displays ignorance,
carelessness or serious negligence.</P1> 
<P1>e. The whole of the merchant's conduct must be analyzed to determine
whether the imperatives of prevention justify an award of punitive damages.</P1>

<P1>f. The amount of the award of punitive damages must be rationally connected
to the purposes for which the punitive damages are awarded. Rationally connected
factors include: whether the merchant was diligent in observing its obligations
under the consumer protection legislation; the seriousness of the violation,
whether the merchant manifested disregard for its obligations; whether the
merchant's conduct was willful or intentional; how the merchant responded to the
consumer's complaint or grievance; and whether the merchant provided
explanations or justifications for the violation.</P1></P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
<COMMENT POSITION="SO2002c30SchA:102(1)" ADDDATE="20210307" LANG="EN" MODDATE="20210316">
<N>102(1)</N>
<TI>Case Law: Section 102(1)</TI>
<SCOPE>S. ^SO2002c30SchA 102(1)</SCOPE>
<FREEFORM>
<P><CASEREF CCDBNUM="1498111">
<SOC>Consumer's Choice Home Improvement Corp. v. Ontario</SOC>
<CITE>2013 ONSC 5600</CITE>
<CORRELAT>
<CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 13874</CITE>
</CORRELAT>
<COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR>
</CASEREF></P>
<P>Pursuant to s. ^SO2002c30SchA 102(1) of the CPA and s. ^OReg17/05 88 of O.
Reg. 17/05, the Minister or Director is given the power to post on a provincial
website for a period of not less than 21 and not more than 27 months, the fact
that a party has been charged under the CPA. In addition, if that party is
convicted, the Director or Minister is given the power to post the fact of that
conviction on the provincial website for a period of not less than 21 and not
more than 27 months. The charge and conviction are treated separately for the
purpose of posting on the website. A restrictive interpretation of s.
^SO2002c30SchA 102(1) of the CPA works to defeat the Minister's ability to
educate and advise consumers, and thus should not be adopted.</P>
</FREEFORM>
</COMMENT>
